<Base title="About ostk" description="A distributed operating system for AI agents. Unix-inspired. Local-first. Invisible by design.">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>About ostk</h1>

    <h2>The OS for AI agents</h2>
    <p>Not a framework. Not a wrapper. A distributed operating system &mdash; the kind that disappears the moment it works.</p>
    <p>Agents read from your filesystem, write to your filesystem, and coordinate with other agents through your filesystem. The kernel resolves conflicts, tracks every edit, enforces capability boundaries, compresses output, manages session lifecycle, and maintains an append-only audit trail. The agents don't know any of this is happening. That's the design.</p>

    <h2>What it does</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fleet coordination</strong> &mdash; spawn, drain, reap, and rehydrate agents across daemon restarts. Workers crash-recover from drain snapshots automatically.</li>
      <li><strong>Optimistic concurrency</strong> &mdash; agents write concurrently. The kernel detects conflicts via generation counters and resolves via Hot PR. No locks held during the expensive phase.</li>
      <li><strong>Output compression</strong> &mdash; three-tier pipeline strips ANSI, deduplicates, and classifies tool output. ~80% token savings on build logs.</li>
      <li><strong>Capability enforcement</strong> &mdash; deny-based pins at the tool layer. Process-level sandboxing via Landlock/Seatbelt at the syscall layer. Two independent layers, defense in depth.</li>
      <li><strong>Identity and trust</strong> &mdash; GPG-based trust chain from hardware identity to human attestation. Four trust tiers. Dual-signed primefile ceremony for governance changes.</li>
      <li><strong>Sub-stack isolation</strong> &mdash; multi-worker tasks run in scoped sub-stacks with their own audit log, drain directory, and token budget. Budget overruns force-seal the stack. The anchor is unaffected.</li>
      <li><strong>Prompt cache economics</strong> &mdash; byte-stable system prefix shared across the fleet via Anthropic's content-addressed cache. Fleet cost scales sublinearly &mdash; adding agents decreases per-agent cost.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The story</h2>
    <p>ostk wasn't designed in a planning meeting. It was extracted from the problem it solves.</p>
    <p>The kernel started as a coordination layer for AI agents working on the same codebase. The first version handled file conflicts. Then process supervision. Then output compression. Then identity, heartbeat, audit trails, scheduling, drain snapshots, crash recovery, sub-stacks, and fleet-wide cache sharing.</p>
    <p>At some point the tool stack disappeared. No more Jira for tracking. No more Slack for coordination. No more separate CI. The OS had absorbed it all &mdash; not by replacing each tool deliberately, but because each problem had a simpler solution when the OS already knew about every agent, every file, and every write.</p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>
    <p>Seven kernel primitives built on Unix-inspired filesystem operations. Five laws that every design decision must satisfy. A six-tier memory hierarchy from model context window to cold audit storage. A dual-CPU scheduler that treats human operators and LLM agents as peer execution resources.</p>
    <p>The full architecture is documented at <a href="/docs/kernel-spec">Kernel Specification</a> and <a href="/docs/session-topology">Session Topology</a>.</p>

    <h2>Source availability</h2>
    <p>The kernel source is not currently published. An open source release under a dual license is planned. The binary is free to use for personal and internal commercial use. See <a href="/legal/license">License</a> for the full terms.</p>
    <p>Governance documents, signing keys, install script, and this site are public. All security findings, trust chain, and verification artifacts are fully available.</p>

